title: Laser Dot - Pan & Tilt Gimbal (simple printing, involved integration)

description.text:
This thing has only two printed parts, but suddenly a couple of stepper motors and a laser pointer engine become biaxial gimbal for remotely putting a red dot on whatever you want! (Or where your cat might want it: http://youtu.be/KbmjemYGDg4) How you use it is up to you. You'll need stepper motor drivers and some kind of controller to tell them what to do. My set up is an Arduino talking through a couple of EasyDrivers. The laser I used is a Quarton Laser Module VLM-650-03 LPA Things to buy:
  • NEMA 8 Stepper
  • NEMA 17 Stepper
  • 4X M2 x 8 screws for the NEMA 8 stepper
  • a 7mm diameter laser head
  • 3X #6-32 x .375" oval point set screws
    • Good to have around:
  • Drill bits that match the shaft sizes of the motors to clean up the parts.
  • A #6-32 tap to cut threads for the set screws
    • Put a dot on it!
For both parts, the flat side with the driven motor shaft hole goes against the glass.

Giant Microbe Light Bulbs from the anime Moyasimon   
I cut a hole in his head to insert the light - see the instructions for sizing tips for your lights
The files provided are sized for the CVS mini Christmas lights (the super cheap ones). However, I suggest you do a test print to scale your bulbs first so that they can be press fit onto your lights.

• Print just the light guide and see if it fits your lights.
  • The most important part of the light guide is to make sure the ring fits snugly over the widest part of the light. If the 4 crown pieces on the top snap off don't worry about it.
  • If the light guide doesn't fit, then scale the light guide until it fits. Remember the scale factor that you used because you will scale the moyasimon light bulb file by the same scale factor
  • Scale the light bulb by the same factor you used in (3)
  • Print the microbe on its back with RAFT and SUPPORT (the file should open with him already in the optimal print position)

• Remove the support materials with some needle nose pliers. I pulled them from his mouth and out of the top of his head. Don't worry too much about removing all the support material.
  • Press the light bulb onto your christmas light. It should be a snug fit, and it should be able to rotate a bit once it is over the widest part of the light.
  • If the bulb is falling off then add a little bit of hot glue on the backside. If the bulb is too small, you should just print it bigger :)

• The support material is can be removed easily if the support walls run parallel to the mouth opening. If this sounds confusing print 2 lights, but rotate one of them 90 degrees on the Z-axis and then see which support material is easier to remove.
  • Copy the bulbs to fill the entire print bed - it took about 10 hours to print 12 bulbs at once (3 x 4 matrix)
  • I printed in clear ABS for the best light diffusion, but opaque white ABS might look cool too (I haven't tried it)
  • There are two files Moyasimon files. I recommend using the regular file WITHOUT the guide. It's more efficient to print the bulbs without the guide and just use hot glue to secure the light. The file with the guide was an early test, and may be of academic interest to some of you. The guides make the support material harder to remove, and don't really add much mechanical support.

description.text:
Updates
April 4th 2015: Remove the hole for Hex nut because the nut was breaking the part when it twisted
Summary:
The great part with this extruder is that the filament is properly guided to the hobbed bolt.
I was fed up with standard Greg's extruder where i nearly needed to remove the pressure screws every time i wanted to change my filament.
With this system that question is obsolete as the filament is always properly guided from the dedicated top hole, to the bottom hole.
The hobbed bolt will always get some grips to the filament even if the teeth as slightly on the side of the filament. This extruder also reduced the different "clicks" you can have with standard extruder.
Plus the stepper motor will find it easy to push the filament as somehow the force needed to push the filament is reduced. Try it for yourself and you will enjoy it! Changes
I made some changes from the original part http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:456025.
-I took the 3mm filament version.
-I added a hole for Jhead hot end at the bottom and 2 side hole for support screws.
-I added some supports so that you don't need to generate any support.
The generated support will bother you with the inside of the part anyway.
The newly added support can be removed easily (see in orange the parts to remove on the pictures) -I increased the hole dedicated to stepper motor central axis.
You could have troubles with the small gear wheels with the side screw hitting the edges of this hole.

Bracket to hold a typical inductive sensor so a metal bed's Z height can be probed. UPDATE:
Please also see my new more accurate Z-probe modification here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1438782
Simply print out the bracket, fit the sensor into the bracket then mount in place of belt clamp, followed by some final adjustments. No modifications to the printer or other hardware is necessary.

The bracket is designed to be the correct size, if you print in PLA it will be perfect, but if you print in ABS you will need to increase the size slightly to allow for shrinkage. It is designed so that the bracket can be printed without supports.

Place one of the nuts from your sensor inside the bracket by inserting in the top and rotating it until its horizontal with the help of a screwdriver or other tool (see photos). You can then screw the sensor inside the nut in the bracket (being sure not to cross-thread it) up until it reaches a depth where the bracket can be easily fitted without the sensor hitting the bed when the carriage is fully lowered (we will adjust properly later). Once you have it the correct height fit the spring washer and remaining nut on the bottom and loosely tighten.

description.header: Fitting the bracket to your X carriage
description.text: Loosen the belt tensioner and remove the existing belt clamp. Using the same bolt that held down your original belt clamp fit this bracket over the belt in the same way you would have with the original belt clamp then tighten up. There is an additional hole to secure it further back but I have found this is not necessary. Once its all in place re-tighten up your belt using the adjuster.

Move your print head down until the nozzle is touching the bed then adjust the sensors height by screwing it up and down until it is roughly just over 1mm from the bed. Once its in the right place tighten up the lock nut on the bottom to secure it.

For further information please check out Thomas Sanladerers excellent video here:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EcGFLwj0pnA

Updates:
-Dec 21th 2014: Add a 3rd version of the clip with longer termination that go up to the end of the 30mm extrusion. It can be usefull when 2 sets of cables are going into 2 different extrusion holes. You will find 2 types of clips here:
-Extrusion_Clip.stl is a simple clip (10mm height) compatible with 3030 extrusion profiles.
-Extrusion_Clip_2.stl is a modified clip with a guide that fit inside the hole of the extrusion profiles. It's also 10mm high.
-Extrusion_Clip_3.stl: is the same as Clip_2 but with additional side length so attempt to clip possible cables on laying on the 2 adjacent sides of the extrusion profile. The other version with 5mm at the end of the names are for the versions of the clips that are only 5mm high.

You can print them with 20% infill, the border thickness is 2mm.
On my side i print with 1mm shell, 20% infill, in PLA.
Any other hard material should work.
